corrected_text: Some notes on K-ras mutations in lung cancer The K-ms signal transduction pathway helps regulate proliferation, apoptosis, and differentiation, all of which are aberrant in cancer. The K-ras gene contains three mutation hotspots which occur at codons 12, 13, and 59-61, and a single point mutation at these sites may activate the K-ras gene. Codon 12 point mutations in K-ras are considered to be an important early stage genetic change in adenocarcinoma of the lung, but rarely occur in squamous cell carcinomas. K-ras mutations appear to be an independent prognostic factor indicating a poor prognosis, independent of stage and histology. Most studies suggest that K-ras mutations occur in about 30% of lung adenocarcinomas in smokers, but are seldom present in adenocarcinomas from nonsmokers. Few K-ras mutations are found in adenocarcinoma of the lung with unknown etiology, or in nonsmokers exposed to radon. Keohavong et af. (Clin. Cancer Res., 2, 411-418, 1996) reported 43 (33.9%) of 173 human jung tumors from a U.S. population to contain codon 12, 18 and 61 mutations. Of these, 41 (82%} of 127 adenocarcinomas contained mutations compared to only 1 squamous carcinoma (2.7%) and 1 adenosquamous carcinoma (11%); 24 of 40 codon 12 mutations consisted of it transversions, 12 GoA transitions, 2 go transversions, and 1 double GG>TT mutation. Two GoT transversions were found in codon 13, and a single AC transversion in codon 61, Husgafvel-Pursiainen et af. (Int. J. Cancer, 58, 250-256, 1993) reported 14 (29%) of 48 Finish lung cancer cases to have K-ras mutations, of these 12 (57%) of 21 adenocarcinoma contained mutations in codons 12, 13 and 61. In a Dutch study, sleeps etal. (N. Engl. J. Med., 323, 561-565, 1990) reported 19 (27.5%) of 69 adenocarcinomas to have K-ras mutations . K-ras mutations have also been suggested to occur in a significant number of squamous cell carcinomas. resell et af, (Clin. Cancer Res., 2, 1083-1086, 1996) have reported 57 (20.7%) of 275 consecutively treated Spanish stage I-IV NSCLCs patients had K-ras mutations in codons 12 and 61, Of these, 20 (26%) of 78 adenocarcinomas, 29 (18%) of 168 squamous call carcinomas, and 8 (23.5%) of large cell undifferentiated carcinomas had K-ras mutations. Codon 12 mutations occurred in 53 (83%) of 57 tumors and were characterized by 14 coding changes from wild-type glycine (GGT) to valine (GTT), 13 to spastic acid (GAT), 10 to cysteine (TET), 8 to serine (AGT), 6 to arginine (CGT) and a single change to alanine (CT). Only 8 (7%) of 57 K-ras mutations occurred at codon 61. Most published studies have specifically investigated K-ras mutations in codon 12, because these are the most frequently detected was mutations in adenocarcinoma of the tung. Analyzing only codon 12 mutations, shine et af. (Carcinogenesis, 17, 1683-1686, 1996} reported 10 (19%) of 53 adenocarcinomas in Japanese males and 2 (4%) of 81 adenocarcinomas in Japanese females to contain K-ras mutations. Of the 12 K-ras mutations, 7 (68%) were G>T transversion, 3 (25%) were GA transitions and 2 (17%) were go transversions. Determining only code 12 mutations results in a slight, but probably not significant, underestimation of the total frequency of K-ras mutations in lung tumors.
